dev/plans/runs/12-TX-review-20260517T205439Z.log:4404:dev/plans/runs/G3_5-cache-pressure-telemetry-20260504T144523Z.log:82:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CQpbp66HhoogP1aD9hVepE","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t{\n2\t  \"phase\": \"G.1\",\n3\t  \"decision_self\": \"INCONCLUSIVE\",\n4\t  \"decision_self_rationale\": \"AC-017 + AC-018 stayed green. Concurrent_median improved 168 ms -> 161 ms (-7 ms, ~4.2%) and speedup_median improved 3.339x -> 3.530x (+0.191x, no ratio worsening). Per handoff §6 / §8 the KEEP threshold is `concurrent_median < baseline - 1*stddev` = 168 - 11.89 = 156.11 ms; observed 161 ms misses the threshold by 4.89 ms (less than half a stddev). Movement is in the right direction but inside the noise band, so the implementer self-decision is INCONCLUSIVE. Lookaside-applied evidence captured below for the orchestrator + codex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer to confirm KEEP-or-REVERT.\",\n5\t  \"commit_sha\": \"46e3576ba92047b68d1a8c8163e580e065871d8d\",\n6\t  \"branch\": \"pack6G-G1-20260504T135138Z\",\n7\t  \"host_caveat\": \"Same worktree host as G.0 (Linux 5.15-tegra, schedutil, ~3x slower than the Pack 5 reference machine). Cross-pack comparisons should use ratios, not absolute ms.\",\n8\t  \"red_tests_written\": [\n9\t    {\n10\t      \"name\": \"reader_workers_have_lookaside_configured_with_ok_rc\",\n11\t      \"file\": \"src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/reader_pool.rs\",\n12\t      \"red_failure_mode\": \"Compile-time: method `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` does not exist on `fathomdb_engine::Engine` (E0599). Pre-implementation. Asserts the rc of `sqlite3_db_config(LOOKASIDE)` captured at open time is SQLITE_OK (0) for every reader worker.\"\n13\t    },\n14\t    {\n15\t      \"name\": \"reader_workers_consume_lookaside_slots_after_warmup_read\",\n16\t      \"file\": \"src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/reader_pool.rs\",\n17\t      \"red_failure_mode\": \"Compile-time: method `reader_lookaside_used_per_worker_for_test` does not exist on `fathomdb_engine::Engine` (E0599). Pre-implementation. Once compiling, this test would also fail at runtime if lookaside were misconfigured (e.g. ordered after a PRAGMA so SQLite silently ignored it) because `SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr would remain 0 after warmup. Initially also failed at runtime when the test read `current` instead of `hiwtr` (slots returned to the pool when the search transaction closed) — fixed by asserting on hiwtr, which is the right semantic for 'at least one slot was honored at any point'.\"\n18\t    }\n19\t  ],\n20\t  \"lookaside_config\": {\n21\t    \"slot_size_bytes\": 1200,\n22\t    \"slot_count\": 500,\n23\t    \"applied_via\": \"raw FFI: rusqlite::ffi::sqlite3_db_config(handle, ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, NULL, 1200, 500). rusqlite 0.31's safe `set_db_config` wrapper only supports the boolean DbConfig::* variants; `SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` is explicitly commented out in `rusqlite-0.31.0/src/config.rs`. Used the named symbol `ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` (= 1001) rather than a magic number per cross-platform Rust convention.\",\n24\t    \"ordering_assertion_rc\": \"0 (SQLITE_OK) for every reader worker, captured at open time before any PRAGMA / prepare ran on the connection. Captured per-worker into `Engine::reader_lookaside_rcs: Vec<i32>` (allow(dead_code) in release; read by `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` in debug).\"\n25\t  },\n26\t  \"lookaside_used_evidence\": {\n27\t    \"method\": \"Debug-only `ReaderRequest::LookasideStatus` request broadcast to every worker (not round-robin); each worker calls `sqlite3_db_status(SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED)` and returns the high-water-mark out-param. `current` was tried first but decays as transactions finalize so it is unreliable for post-warmup evidence; `hiwtr` is the correct latched signal that lookaside was honored at any point.\",\n28\t    \"after_warmup_test_workload\": \"READER_POOL_SIZE * 8 = 64 dispatched `engine.search('warmup')` calls (each routed round-robin to one of the 8 workers) on a fresh empty engine, search() returns Err but still parses + prepares + steps which exercises the lookaside arena.\",\n29\t    \"hiwtr_per_worker\": [57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57],\n30\t    \"interpretation\": \"Every worker has hiwtr=57 slots used (well below the configured 500-slot capacity, ~11%). Uniformity across workers reflects the round-robin dispatch + the fact that `engine.search('warmup')` exercises the same transaction shape on each. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload is more allocation-heavy and would push hiwtr higher; the test gate is 'consumed > 0', not 'saturated'.\"\n31\t  },\n32\t  \"ac017_runs\": [\n33\t    {\n34\t      \"passed\": true,\n35\t      \"profile\": \"release\",\n36\t      \"notes\": \"Run via `cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture`; `test ac_017_vector_projection_freshness_p99_le_five_seconds ... ok` in 14.64 s wall.\"\n37\t    }\n38\t  ],\n39\t  \"ac018_runs\": [\n40\t    {\n41\t      \"drain_ms\": 95,\n42\t      \"passed\": true,\n43\t      \"notes\": \"release; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95; well under the 2 s gate. Slightly higher than G.0's 51 ms (run-to-run; G.0 itself reported 56 ms in F.0 baseline).\"\n44\t    }\n45\t  ],\n46\t  \"ac020_runs\": [\n47\t    {\"run\": 1, \"sequential_ms\": 582, \"concurrent_ms\": 153, \"bound_ms\": 109, \"speedup\": 3.804, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n48\t    {\"run\": 2, \"sequential_ms\": 547, \"concurrent_ms\": 161, \"bound_ms\": 102, \"speedup\": 3.398, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n49\t    {\"run\": 3, \"sequential_ms\": 593, \"concurrent_ms\": 168, \"bound_ms\": 111, \"speedup\": 3.530, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n50\t    {\"run\": 4, \"sequential_ms\": 563, \"concurrent_ms\": 181, \"bound_ms\": 105, \"speedup\": 3.110, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n51\t    {\"run\": 5, \"sequential_ms\": 503, \"concurrent_ms\": 118, \"bound_ms\": 94,  \"speedup\": 4.263, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false}\n52\t  ],\n53\t  \"ac020_summary\": {\n54\t    \"sequential_ms\": {\"min\": 503, \"median\": 563, \"max\": 593, \"stddev\": 33.40},\n55\t    \"concurrent_ms\": {\"min\": 118, \"median\": 161, \"max\": 181, \"stddev\": 22.83},\n56\t    \"speedup\":      {\"min\": 3.110, \"median\": 3.530, \"max\": 4.263, \"stddev\": 0.428}\n57\t  },\n58\t  \"comparison_to_g0_baseline\": {\n59\t    \"g0_baseline_of_record\": {\n60\t      \"sequential_ms_median\": 552,\n61\t      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 168,\n62\t      \"speedup_median\": 3.339,\n63\t      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 11.89,\n64\t      \"n\": 5\n65\t    },\n66\t    \"g1_observed\": {\n67\t      \"sequential_ms_median\": 563,\n68\t      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 161,\n69\t      \"speedup_median\": 3.530,\n70\t      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 22.83,\n71\t      \"n\": 5\n72\t    },\n73\t    \"deltas\": {\n74\t      \"sequential_ms_median_delta\": \"+11 ms (+2.0%) — within run-to-run noise\",\n75\t      \"concurrent_ms_median_delta\": \"-7 ms (-4.2%) — improvement, but inside G.0's 1*stddev band (11.89 ms)\",\n76\t      \"speedup_median_delta\": \"+0.191x (+5.7%) — no ratio worsening\",\n77\t      \"concurrent_ms_stddev_delta\": \"+10.94 ms — G.1 run shows higher variance, partly driven by run 5 (118 ms) and run 4 (181 ms); not a regression but a wider band that loosens the KEEP threshold further on this sample\"\n78\t    },\n79\t    \"keep_threshold_evaluation\": {\n80\t      \"rule\": \"concurrent_median < g0_baseline.concurrent_median - 1 * g0_baseline.stddev\",\n81\t      \"threshold_ms\": 156.11,\n82\t      \"observed_ms\": 161,\n83\t      \"verdict\": \"miss by 4.89 ms (~0.41 * stddev); does NOT meet KEEP threshold\",\n84\t      \"ratio_floor_evaluation\": {\n85\t        \"rule\": \"speedup_median >= g0_baseline.speedup_median\",\n86\t        \"threshold\": 3.339,\n87\t        \"observed\": 3.530,\n88\t        \"verdict\": \"pass; no ratio worsening\"\n89\t      }\n90\t    }\n91\t  },\n92\t  \"optional_sweep_results\": null,\n93\t  \"optional_sweep_notes\": \"Did not run the [128, 250, 500, 1000] x {512, 1200} sweep grid. Spec §2 makes it optional ('do NOT bake the sweep into the production code path'); G.0 telemetry already pointed at 1200 x 500 as the right canonical sizing for the sticky reader topology and the small-allocation footprint of the FTS5 / vec0 hot stacks. If the orchestrator + reviewer want the sweep before deciding KEEP vs INCONCLUSIVE, it can be done as a follow-up under a debug-gated env knob without re-opening the public surface; the lookaside-call helper is already isolated in `configure_reader_lookaside`.\",\n94\t  \"unexpected_observations\": [\n95\t    \"AC-020 run-to-run variance widened on this G.1 sample (concurrent stddev 22.83 ms vs G.0's 11.89 ms). Run 5 in particular hit 118 ms / 4.263x — the best concurrent number observed in any G-phase run on this host so far — while run 4 hit 181 ms / 3.110x. The wider band loosens the formal KEEP threshold but suggests lookaside is doing real work when contention is the bottleneck (run 5 is plausibly an arena-pressure best-case). A larger N (e.g. N=10) would tighten the verdict; the spec calls for N=5 so I did not run more.\",\n96\t    \"Sequential_median moved +11 ms (552 -> 563). Within noise, but consistent with the documented 'lookaside has a small overhead per allocation when the slot pool is healthy' note in the SQLite docs; sequential perf shouldn't IMPROVE from lookaside on a single-threaded fixture (no malloc-arena contention to remove), and a small regression in the 1-2% band is expected and tolerable.\",\n97\t    \"Per-worker `LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr after warmup is uniform at 57 slots/worker, which is ~11% of the 500-slot capacity. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload would push that higher (the warmup test does only a 64-call light-search loop on an empty DB). Slot_count 500 may be over-provisioned for the warmup fixture but well-sized for AC-020 + the FTS5/vec0 stacks visible in the G.0 top-call-site table. No evidence of a `LOOKASIDE_MISS_FULL` wall.\",\n98\t    \"AC-018 drain_ms moved from 51 ms (G.0 release run) to 95 ms (G.1 release run). Still trivially under the 2 s gate, no contract impact, but worth noting if the 6.G synthesis tracks AC-018 trend. Likely host-jitter; the writer connection does NOT have lookaside applied in this packet (G.1 scope is reader-side only).\"\n99\t  ],\n100\t  \"alternative_hypothesis_if_revert\": \"If a follow-on run on the orchestrator side shows the concurrent_median improvement does NOT reproduce (i.e. observed median > 168 + 1 * stddev), the most likely explanation is that the dominant residual on AC-020 is NOT the glibc malloc-arena mutex but the SQLite pcache1 global mutex (G.0 reported `page_cache` = 6.29% conc with 4.01x ratio, the second-largest contention class). Lookaside reduces calls to `pcache1Alloc -> sqlite3Malloc -> __libc_malloc` but does NOT eliminate the pcache1 mutex itself, which still sits on the page-fetch hot path. Per the G.0 unexpected_observations, a per-connection (private) page cache (`PRAGMA private_cache=ON` / `SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE`) would attack that residual; that's a candidate G.4. The G.1 numbers being just below the 1*stddev threshold are consistent with this: lookaside removed some malloc-arena calls but the pcache1-mutex floor is still there.\",\n101\t  \"data_for_pivot\": {\n102\t    \"if_keep\": {\n103\t      \"next_lever\": \"G.4 — per-connection (private) page cache. G.0 telemetry called this out: page_cache (pcache1Fetch / Unpin / Alloc / Destroy) shows 4.01x growth concurrent vs sequential and is the second-largest contention path after allocator_lookaside. Lookaside masks pcache1Alloc fall-through to malloc but not the pcache1 global mutex itself. Canonical-SQLite lever: `SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE` open flag or `PRAGMA cache=private` per-reader-connection. Distinct from the §3 do-not-retry `cache_size` global tuning entry.\",\n104\t      \"deferred\": \"G.2 (per-worker prepared-statement cache, sticky-connection revisit of E.1) is still motivated by parse_compile = 22.52% conc, but its ratio is 0.61 (share shrinks under concurrency), so it lowers a CPU floor more than it removes a contention point. Defer until G.4 settles.\"\n105\t    },\n106\t    \"if_revert_or_inconclusive\": {\n107\t      \"recommended_orchestrator_action\": \"Run an independent N=5 confirmation pass on the same commit with the same agent-verify-style guardrails. If the second pass reproduces concurrent_median ~ 161 ms (one stddev above the KEEP threshold), this is genuinely lookaside-improving-allocator-pressure but the F.0 baseline's 11.89 ms stddev was tighter than reality; KEEP on a relaxed 'concurrent_median < baseline AND speedup_median > baseline' rule is defensible (movement direction + ratio floor both pass). If the second pass shows no movement or regression, REVERT and pivot directly to G.4 (private page cache) since allocator-arena is then NOT the rate-limiting residual on this host.\",\n108\t      \"reviewer_specific_notes_for_codex_gpt54_high\": \"Lookaside is not on the §5 do-not-retry list. No public Rust API expansion: only `#[cfg(debug_assertions)] #[doc(hidden)]` test accessors per F.0 reviewer convention, and one debug-only `ReaderRequest` variant. FFI uses `c_int` per `feedback_cross_platform_rust.md`; named symbol `ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` not magic 1001. Ordering rc captured + debug-asserted before any PRAGMA / prepare runs. AC-018 unchanged (still green, drain 95 ms). Same-snapshot cursor contract / AC-021 / AC-022 / AC-059b untouched (no read-path SQL or transaction-shape changes).\"\n109\t    }\n110\t  },\n111\t  \"agent_verify_status\": \"pass\",\n112\t  \"agent_verify_reason\": \"`./scripts/agent-verify.sh` (per F.0 reviewer block #3 — NOT `dev/agent-verify.sh`) returned rc=0 on a clean run. First fmt run flagged a rustfmt-style block-vs-inline struct expansion on the new `LookasideStatus` ReaderRequest variant; fixed by running `cargo fmt --all` and re-running. AC-017 + AC-018 release-profile runs both green prior to the AC-020 capture (AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95).\",\n113\t  \"do_not_retry_cross_check\": [\n114\t    {\"item\": \"B.1 runtime sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)\",                 \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"G.1 only adds `sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE)` — a per-connection allocator setting. No `sqlite3_config` (capital-C global) calls were added or modified. `git log -p f1e66bc..46e3576 -- src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs` shows no SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD touch.\"},\n115\t    {\"item\": \"C.1 compile-time SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2 rebuild\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No libsqlite3-sys / build.rs / Cargo.toml feature changes; canonical SQLite serialized mode unchanged. No reproducible-bin layer touched.\"},\n116\t    {\"item\": \"E.1 read-path prepare_cached on borrow/release pool connections\",      \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No prepare_cached changes anywhere in this commit. G.2 (sticky thread-affine prepared cache) is still future-packet.\"},\n117\t    {\"item\": \"Reader cache_size / mmap_size global tuning\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No PRAGMA cache_size / mmap_size production-default changes. Only PRAGMAs touched on reader connections at open are the pre-existing journal_mode=WAL + query_only=ON; nothing added.\"},\n118\t    {\"item\": \"Reader open flags READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX\",                               \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"Reader open flags untouched: still `Connection::open(&path)` with default flags. Lookaside is a per-connection allocator setting, not an open-flag bit; the §3 NO_MUTEX entry is unrelated and stays not-retried.\"}\n119\t  ],\n120\t  \"tests_run\": [\n121\t    \"cargo build --tests -p fathomdb-engine — green\",\n122\t    \"cargo test -p fathomdb-engine --test reader_pool (6 tests, all green; 2 new G.1 lookaside tests + the 4 existing F.0 worker-pool tests)\",\n123\t    \"cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture — both green; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95\",\n124\t    \"AGENT_LONG=1 cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates ac_020_reads_do_not_serialize -- --nocapture --test-threads=1 (x5) — gate fails as expected (still chasing 5.33x), all numerics captured\",\n125\t    \"cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings — clean\",\n126\t    \"cargo fmt --all -- --check — clean\",\n127\t    \"./scripts/agent-verify.sh — rc=0\"\n128\t  ],\n129\t  \"next_phase_input\": {\n130\t    \"for_orchestrator\": \"Codex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer mandatory on this INCONCLUSIVE per handoff §7. If the reviewer + orchestrator KEEP, pivot to G.4 (private page cache) — that lever attacks the second-largest G.0 contention class (`page_cache` 6.29% conc with 4.01x ratio) and is canonical-SQLite (`SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE` / `PRAGMA cache=private`), distinct from the §3 do-not-retry `cache_size` global tuning entry. If the reviewer REVERTS, the same G.4 candidate becomes the next phase since the residual is then NOT allocator-arena.\",\n131\t    \"for_packet_close\": \"G.1 is a small-radius lever; if it KEEPs the cumulative speedup vs F.0 is ~+0.19x (3.339x -> 3.530x). AC-020's 5.33x KEEP target / 5.0x packet floor is still ~1.5-1.8x away. Per handoff §9, packet success is 'every canonical-SQLite lever tried, KEEPs landed, residual gap documented for Pack 7' — not 'AC-020 closes within 0.6.0'.\"\n132\t  }\n133\t}\n134\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"485c34a8-dceb-42a9-9d76-fb4335ae2dfc","uuid":"79e8b266-161c-4a4b-82a0-bc9349c96d40","timestamp":"2026-05-04T14:45:55.017Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-pack6G-G3_5-20260504T144523Z/dev/plan/runs/G1-reader-lookaside-output.json","content":"{\n  \"phase\": \"G.1\",\n  \"decision_self\": \"INCONCLUSIVE\",\n  \"decision_self_rationale\": \"AC-017 + AC-018 stayed green. Concurrent_median improved 168 ms -> 161 ms (-7 ms, ~4.2%) and speedup_median improved 3.339x -> 3.530x (+0.191x, no ratio worsening). Per handoff §6 / §8 the KEEP threshold is `concurrent_median < baseline - 1*stddev` = 168 - 11.89 = 156.11 ms; observed 161 ms misses the threshold by 4.89 ms (less than half a stddev). Movement is in the right direction but inside the noise band, so the implementer self-decision is INCONCLUSIVE. Lookaside-applied evidence captured below for the orchestrator + codex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer to confirm KEEP-or-REVERT.\",\n  \"commit_sha\": \"46e3576ba92047b68d1a8c8163e580e065871d8d\",\n  \"branch\": \"pack6G-G1-20260504T135138Z\",\n  \"host_caveat\": \"Same worktree host as G.0 (Linux 5.15-tegra, schedutil, ~3x slower than the Pack 5 reference machine). Cross-pack comparisons should use ratios, not absolute ms.\",\n  \"red_tests_written\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"reader_workers_have_lookaside_configured_with_ok_rc\",\n      \"file\": \"src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/reader_pool.rs\",\n      \"red_failure_mode\": \"Compile-time: method `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` does not exist on `fathomdb_engine::Engine` (E0599). Pre-implementation. Asserts the rc of `sqlite3_db_config(LOOKASIDE)` captured at open time is SQLITE_OK (0) for every reader worker.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"reader_workers_consume_lookaside_slots_after_warmup_read\",\n      \"file\": \"src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/reader_pool.rs\",\n      \"red_failure_mode\": \"Compile-time: method `reader_lookaside_used_per_worker_for_test` does not exist on `fathomdb_engine::Engine` (E0599). Pre-implementation. Once compiling, this test would also fail at runtime if lookaside were misconfigured (e.g. ordered after a PRAGMA so SQLite silently ignored it) because `SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr would remain 0 after warmup. Initially also failed at runtime when the test read `current` instead of `hiwtr` (slots returned to the pool when the search transaction closed) — fixed by asserting on hiwtr, which is the right semantic for 'at least one slot was honored at any point'.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"lookaside_config\": {\n    \"slot_size_bytes\": 1200,\n    \"slot_count\": 500,\n    \"applied_via\": \"raw FFI: rusqlite::ffi::sqlite3_db_config(handle, ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, NULL, 1200, 500). rusqlite 0.31's safe `set_db_config` wrapper only supports the boolean DbConfig::* variants; `SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` is explicitly commented out in `rusqlite-0.31.0/src/config.rs`. Used the named symbol `ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` (= 1001) rather than a magic number per cross-platform Rust convention.\",\n    \"ordering_assertion_rc\": \"0 (SQLITE_OK) for every reader worker, captured at open time before any PRAGMA / prepare ran on the connection. Captured per-worker into `Engine::reader_lookaside_rcs: Vec<i32>` (allow(dead_code) in release; read by `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` in debug).\"\n  },\n  \"lookaside_used_evidence\": {\n    \"method\": \"Debug-only `ReaderRequest::LookasideStatus` request broadcast to every worker (not round-robin); each worker calls `sqlite3_db_status(SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED)` and returns the high-water-mark out-param. `current` was tried first but decays as transactions finalize so it is unreliable for post-warmup evidence; `hiwtr` is the correct latched signal that lookaside was honored at any point.\",\n    \"after_warmup_test_workload\": \"READER_POOL_SIZE * 8 = 64 dispatched `engine.search('warmup')` calls (each routed round-robin to one of the 8 workers) on a fresh empty engine, search() returns Err but still parses + prepares + steps which exercises the lookaside arena.\",\n    \"hiwtr_per_worker\": [57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57],\n    \"interpretation\": \"Every worker has hiwtr=57 slots used (well below the configured 500-slot capacity, ~11%). Uniformity across workers reflects the round-robin dispatch + the fact that `engine.search('warmup')` exercises the same transaction shape on each. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload is more allocation-heavy and would push hiwtr higher; the test gate is 'consumed > 0', not 'saturated'.\"\n  },\n  \"ac017_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"profile\": \"release\",\n      \"notes\": \"Run via `cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture`; `test ac_017_vector_projection_freshness_p99_le_five_seconds ... ok` in 14.64 s wall.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ac018_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"drain_ms\": 95,\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"notes\": \"release; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95; well under the 2 s gate. Slightly higher than G.0's 51 ms (run-to-run; G.0 itself reported 56 ms in F.0 baseline).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ac020_runs\": [\n    {\"run\": 1, \"sequential_ms\": 582, \"concurrent_ms\": 153, \"bound_ms\": 109, \"speedup\": 3.804, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 2, \"sequential_ms\": 547, \"concurrent_ms\": 161, \"bound_ms\": 102, \"speedup\": 3.398, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 3, \"sequential_ms\": 593, \"concurrent_ms\": 168, \"bound_ms\": 111, \"speedup\": 3.530, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 4, \"sequential_ms\": 563, \"concurrent_ms\": 181, \"bound_ms\": 105, \"speedup\": 3.110, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 5, \"sequential_ms\": 503, \"concurrent_ms\": 118, \"bound_ms\": 94,  \"speedup\": 4.263, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false}\n  ],\n  \"ac020_summary\": {\n    \"sequential_ms\": {\"min\": 503, \"median\": 563, \"max\": 593, \"stddev\": 33.40},\n    \"concurrent_ms\": {\"min\": 118, \"median\": 161, \"max\": 181, \"stddev\": 22.83},\n    \"speedup\":      {\"min\": 3.110, \"median\": 3.530, \"max\": 4.263, \"stddev\": 0.428}\n  },\n  \"comparison_to_g0_baseline\": {\n    \"g0_baseline_of_record\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median\": 552,\n      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 168,\n      \"speedup_median\": 3.339,\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 11.89,\n      \"n\": 5\n    },\n    \"g1_observed\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median\": 563,\n      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 161,\n      \"speedup_median\": 3.530,\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 22.83,\n      \"n\": 5\n    },\n    \"deltas\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median_delta\": \"+11 ms (+2.0%) — within run-to-run noise\",\n      \"concurrent_ms_median_delta\": \"-7 ms (-4.2%) — improvement, but inside G.0's 1*stddev band (11.89 ms)\",\n      \"speedup_median_delta\": \"+0.191x (+5.7%) — no ratio worsening\",\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev_delta\": \"+10.94 ms — G.1 run shows higher variance, partly driven by run 5 (118 ms) and run 4 (181 ms); not a regression but a wider band that loosens the KEEP threshold further on this sample\"\n    },\n    \"keep_threshold_evaluation\": {\n      \"rule\": \"concurrent_median < g0_baseline.concurrent_median - 1 * g0_baseline.stddev\",\n      \"threshold_ms\": 156.11,\n      \"observed_ms\": 161,\n      \"verdict\": \"miss by 4.89 ms (~0.41 * stddev); does NOT meet KEEP threshold\",\n      \"ratio_floor_evaluation\": {\n        \"rule\": \"speedup_median >= g0_baseline.speedup_median\",\n        \"threshold\": 3.339,\n        \"observed\": 3.530,\n        \"verdict\": \"pass; no ratio worsening\"\n      }\n    }\n  },\n  \"optional_sweep_results\": null,\n  \"optional_sweep_notes\": \"Did not run the [128, 250, 500, 1000] x {512, 1200} sweep grid. Spec §2 makes it optional ('do NOT bake the sweep into the production code path'); G.0 telemetry already pointed at 1200 x 500 as the right canonical sizing for the sticky reader topology and the small-allocation footprint of the FTS5 / vec0 hot stacks. If the orchestrator + reviewer want the sweep before deciding KEEP vs INCONCLUSIVE, it can be done as a follow-up under a debug-gated env knob without re-opening the public surface; the lookaside-call helper is already isolated in `configure_reader_lookaside`.\",\n  \"unexpected_observations\": [\n    \"AC-020 run-to-run variance widened on this G.1 sample (concurrent stddev 22.83 ms vs G.0's 11.89 ms). Run 5 in particular hit 118 ms / 4.263x — the best concurrent number observed in any G-phase run on this host so far — while run 4 hit 181 ms / 3.110x. The wider band loosens the formal KEEP threshold but suggests lookaside is doing real work when contention is the bottleneck (run 5 is plausibly an arena-pressure best-case). A larger N (e.g. N=10) would tighten the verdict; the spec calls for N=5 so I did not run more.\",\n    \"Sequential_median moved +11 ms (552 -> 563). Within noise, but consistent with the documented 'lookaside has a small overhead per allocation when the slot pool is healthy' note in the SQLite docs; sequential perf shouldn't IMPROVE from lookaside on a single-threaded fixture (no malloc-arena contention to remove), and a small regression in the 1-2% band is expected and tolerable.\",\n    \"Per-worker `LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr after warmup is uniform at 57 slots/worker, which is ~11% of the 500-slot capacity. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload would push that higher (the warmup test does only a 64-call light-search loop on an empty DB). Slot_count 500 may be over-provisioned for the warmup fixture but well-sized for AC-020 + the FTS5/vec0 stacks visible in the G.0 top-call-site table. No evidence of a `LOOKASIDE_MISS_FULL` wall.\",\n    \"AC-018 drain_ms moved from 51 ms (G.0 release run) to 95 ms (G.1 release run). Still trivially under the 2 s gate, no contract impact, but worth noting if the 6.G synthesis tracks AC-018 trend. Likely host-jitter; the writer connection does NOT have lookaside applied in this packet (G.1 scope is reader-side only).\"\n  ],\n  \"alternative_hypothesis_if_revert\": \"If a follow-on run on the orchestrator side shows the concurrent_median improvement does NOT reproduce (i.e. observed median > 168 + 1 * stddev), the most likely explanation is that the dominant residual on AC-020 is NOT the glibc malloc-arena mutex but the SQLite pcache1 global mutex (G.0 reported `page_cache` = 6.29% conc with 4.01x ratio, the second-largest contention class). Lookaside reduces calls to `pcache1Alloc -> sqlite3Malloc -> __libc_malloc` but does NOT eliminate the pcache1 mutex itself, which still sits on the page-fetch hot path. Per the G.0 unexpected_observations, a per-connection (private) page cache (`PRAGMA private_cache=ON` / `SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE`) would attack that residual; that's a candidate G.4. The G.1 numbers being just below the 1*stddev threshold are consistent with this: lookaside removed some malloc-arena calls but the pcache1-mutex floor is still there.\",\n  \"data_for_pivot\": {\n    \"if_keep\": {\n      \"next_lever\": \"G.4 — per-connection (private) page cache. G.0 telemetry called this out: page_cache (pcache1Fetch / Unpin / Alloc / Destroy) shows 4.01x growth concurrent vs sequential and is the second-largest contention path after allocator_lookaside. Lookaside masks pcache1Alloc fall-through to malloc but not the pcache1 global mutex itself. Canonical-SQLite lever: `SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE` open flag or `PRAGMA cache=private` per-reader-connection. Distinct from the §3 do-not-retry `cache_size` global tuning entry.\",\n      \"deferred\": \"G.2 (per-worker prepared-statement cache, sticky-connection revisit of E.1) is still motivated by parse_compile = 22.52% conc, but its ratio is 0.61 (share shrinks under concurrency), so it lowers a CPU floor more than it removes a contention point. Defer until G.4 settles.\"\n    },\n    \"if_revert_or_inconclusive\": {\n      \"recommended_orchestrator_action\": \"Run an independent N=5 confirmation pass on the same commit with the same agent-verify-style guardrails. If the second pass reproduces concurrent_median ~ 161 ms (one stddev above the KEEP threshold), this is genuinely lookaside-improving-allocator-pressure but the F.0 baseline's 11.89 ms stddev was tighter than reality; KEEP on a relaxed 'concurrent_median < baseline AND speedup_median > baseline' rule is defensible (movement direction + ratio floor both pass). If the second pass shows no movement or regression, REVERT and pivot directly to G.4 (private page cache) since allocator-arena is then NOT the rate-limiting residual on this host.\",\n      \"reviewer_specific_notes_for_codex_gpt54_high\": \"Lookaside is not on the §5 do-not-retry list. No public Rust API expansion: only `#[cfg(debug_assertions)] #[doc(hidden)]` test accessors per F.0 reviewer convention, and one debug-only `ReaderRequest` variant. FFI uses `c_int` per `feedback_cross_platform_rust.md`; named symbol `ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` not magic 1001. Ordering rc captured + debug-asserted before any PRAGMA / prepare runs. AC-018 unchanged (still green, drain 95 ms). Same-snapshot cursor contract / AC-021 / AC-022 / AC-059b untouched (no read-path SQL or transaction-shape changes).\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"agent_verify_status\": \"pass\",\n  \"agent_verify_reason\": \"`./scripts/agent-verify.sh` (per F.0 reviewer block #3 — NOT `dev/agent-verify.sh`) returned rc=0 on a clean run. First fmt run flagged a rustfmt-style block-vs-inline struct expansion on the new `LookasideStatus` ReaderRequest variant; fixed by running `cargo fmt --all` and re-running. AC-017 + AC-018 release-profile runs both green prior to the AC-020 capture (AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95).\",\n  \"do_not_retry_cross_check\": [\n    {\"item\": \"B.1 runtime sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)\",                 \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"G.1 only adds `sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE)` — a per-connection allocator setting. No `sqlite3_config` (capital-C global) calls were added or modified. `git log -p f1e66bc..46e3576 -- src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs` shows no SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD touch.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"C.1 compile-time SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2 rebuild\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No libsqlite3-sys / build.rs / Cargo.toml feature changes; canonical SQLite serialized mode unchanged. No reproducible-bin layer touched.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"E.1 read-path prepare_cached on borrow/release pool connections\",      \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No prepare_cached changes anywhere in this commit. G.2 (sticky thread-affine prepared cache) is still future-packet.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"Reader cache_size / mmap_size global tuning\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No PRAGMA cache_size / mmap_size production-default changes. Only PRAGMAs touched on reader connections at open are the pre-existing journal_mode=WAL + query_only=ON; nothing added.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"Reader open flags READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX\",                               \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"Reader open flags untouched: still `Connection::open(&path)` with default flags. Lookaside is a per-connection allocator setting, not an open-flag bit; the §3 NO_MUTEX entry is unrelated and stays not-retried.\"}\n  ],\n  \"tests_run\": [\n    \"cargo build --tests -p fathomdb-engine — green\",\n    \"cargo test -p fathomdb-engine --test reader_pool (6 tests, all green; 2 new G.1 lookaside tests + the 4 existing F.0 worker-pool tests)\",\n    \"cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture — both green; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95\",\n    \"AGENT_LONG=1 cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates ac_020_reads_do_not_serialize -- --nocapture --test-threads=1 (x5) — gate fails as expected (still chasing 5.33x), all numerics captured\",\n    \"cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings — clean\",\n    \"cargo fmt --all -- --check — clean\",\n    \"./scripts/agent-verify.sh — rc=0\"\n  ],\n  \"next_phase_input\": {\n    \"for_orchestrator\": \"Codex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer mandatory on this INCONCLUSIVE per handoff §7. If the reviewer + orchestrator KEEP, pivot to G.4 (private page cache) — that lever attacks the second-largest G.0 contention class (`page_cache` 6.29% conc with 4.01x ratio) and is canonical-SQLite (`SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE` / `PRAGMA cache=private`), distinct from the §3 do-not-retry `cache_size` global tuning entry. If the reviewer REVERTS, the same G.4 candidate becomes the next phase since the residual is then NOT allocator-arena.\",\n    \"for_packet_close\": \"G.1 is a small-radius lever; if it KEEPs the cumulative speedup vs F.0 is ~+0.19x (3.339x -> 3.530x). AC-020's 5.33x KEEP target / 5.0x packet floor is still ~1.5-1.8x away. Per handoff §9, packet success is 'every canonical-SQLite lever tried, KEEPs landed, residual gap documented for Pack 7' — not 'AC-020 closes within 0.6.0'.\"\n  }\n}\n","numLines":134,"startLine":1,"totalLines":134}}}
dev/plans/runs/12-TX-review-20260517T205439Z.log:4425:dev/plans/runs/C1-threadsafe2-rebuild-20260504T022727Z.log:38:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FqXbFRfWBQyLSHnrPMGoqT","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# AGENTS.md — FathomDB\n2\t\n3\tOperating manual for AI coding agents (Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, Aider, Copilot) working in this repo. Cross-vendor convention. This is the canonical agent-instruction file; **no `CLAUDE.md` is maintained** — Claude Code reads `AGENTS.md` natively.\n4\t\n5\tBullet form, prescriptive, ≤300 lines. Link out, do not inline.\n6\t\n7\t## 0. System layers — where each rule fits\n8\t\n9\t- **Invariants layer** — this file (front-loaded, cached, ≤300, bullets).\n10\t- **Index layer** — `dev/adr/ADR-0.6.0-decision-index.md`, `dev/interfaces/*.md`. Linked, never inlined.\n11\t- **Retrieval layer** — grep / glob / read / LSP / tree-sitter map on demand. No local vector index.\n12\t- **Execution layer** — typed dev-loop verbs under `scripts/agent-*.sh` emit structured JSON. Tests are oracle.\n13\t- **Persistence layer** — `dev/progress/<release>.md` + ADR supersession. Compaction-safe.\n14\t- **Permission layer** — three-tier sandbox + worktree-per-task + egress allowlist (`.claude/settings.json`).\n15\t- **Topology layer** — main thread orchestrates; implementer (worktree) + code-reviewer fan out at clean seams; single-agent for shared-state edits.\n16\t\n17\t---\n18\t\n19\t## 1. Invariants — read these first\n20\t\n21\t- **Memory first.** Read `MEMORY.md` and the `feedback_*.md` files it points to before planning any change. They encode prior corrections that override default behavior.\n22\t- **ADRs are authoritative.** Decisions live in `dev/adr/`. Index: `dev/adr/ADR-0.6.0-decision-index.md`. Do not contradict an accepted ADR; propose a successor instead.\n23\t- **TDD is mandatory.** Failing test first; red → green → refactor. Mechanical version bumps and renames are the only exception. (`feedback_tdd.md`)\n24\t- **Stale > missing.** A wrong comment, doc, or ADR is more harmful than its absence. If you cannot maintain something, delete it.\n25\t- **Public surface is contract.** Anything in `dev/interfaces/` or `pub` Rust APIs is a contract; changes need an ADR or interface-doc update in the same PR.\n26\t\n27\t## 2. Repo shape\n28\t\n29\t- **Rust workspace** under `src/rust/crates/` — 7 crates: `fathomdb`, `fathomdb-cli`, `fathomdb-engine`, `fathomdb-query`, `fathomdb-schema`, `fathomdb-embedder`, `fathomdb-embedder-api`.\n30\t- **Python bindings** under `src/python/` (package: `fathomdb`).\n31\t- **TypeScript bindings** under `src/ts/`.\n32\t- **Public docs** under `docs/` (MkDocs-built).\n33\t- **Internal engineering docs** under `dev/`: `adr/`, `interfaces/`, `progress/`, `plans/`, `tmp/`.\n34\t\n35\t## 3. Build / test / lint commands\n36\t\n37\tUse the typed dev-loop verbs (Phase 2). Each emits **concise output on pass, structured diagnostic on fail**, with full output spilled to `/tmp/fathomdb-agent-<verb>-<pid>.log` when capped.\n38\t\n39\t| Verb      | Script                         | Purpose                                                           |\n40\t| --------- | ------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------------------------- |\n41\t| build     | `./scripts/agent-build.sh`     | Compile workspace (Rust + Python install + TS build if installed) |\n42\t| lint      | `./scripts/agent-lint.sh`      | clippy + ruff + markdownlint + prettier --check + lychee          |\n43\t| typecheck | `./scripts/agent-typecheck.sh` | cargo check + pyright + tsc --noEmit                              |\n44\t| test      | `./scripts/agent-test.sh`      | cargo test + pytest                                               |\n45\t| verify    | `./scripts/agent-verify.sh`    | lint → typecheck → test (short-circuits on first fail)            |\n46\t\n47\tMarkdown lint covers `AGENTS.md`, `dev/plans/`, `dev/progress/`, README files, and root metadata. Pre-existing legacy under `dev/adr/`, `dev/design/`, `dev/agents/`, `dev/deps/`, etc. is excluded — clean up incrementally when touching those files. Auto-fix: `npm run format:md` (prettier --write) + `./node_modules/.bin/markdownlint-cli2 --fix`.\n48\t\n49\tRun `./scripts/agent-verify.sh` after every meaningful edit. Do not ship a PR with verify failing.\n50\t\n51\tThe broader CI gate is `./scripts/check.sh` (adds mkdocs build); the agent-loop gate is `agent-verify.sh`. Long-run test variants (e.g. AC-021 60 s window, AC-059b ~1000-iteration cursor-race fixture) are exercised only via `scripts/check.sh` with `AGENT_LONG=1`; `agent-verify.sh` skips them for runtime budget.\n52\t\n53\t### One-time setup\n54\t\n55\t- Rust toolchain: stable per `rust-version` in `Cargo.toml`. clippy + rustfmt come with rustup defaults.\n56\t- Python dev tooling: `pip install -e 'src/python[dev]'` — installs `pytest`, `hypothesis`, `ruff`, `pyright`. Without this, the Python lint/typecheck/test steps emit a skip notice and pass without exercising.\n57\t- TypeScript: `cd src/ts && npm install` if you intend to touch TS. Without this, TS verbs skip.\n58\t- Markdown tooling: `npm install` at repo root — installs `markdownlint-cli2` + `prettier`. `cargo install --locked lychee` for link checking (one-time). All wired up by `./scripts/bootstrap.sh`.\n59\t\n60\t## 4. Verification ordering\n61\t\n62\tRun in latency order; short-circuit on first failure:\n63\t\n64\t1. **lint** (clippy / ruff) — fastest signal, catches most style + correctness issues\n65\t2. **typecheck** (cargo check / pyright / tsc) — catches type errors before tests run them\n66\t3. **unit tests** (`agent-test.sh`)\n67\t4. **integration tests** — opt-in, gated by feature/env flag; not part of `agent-verify`\n68\t\n69\tDo not paraphrase, summarize, or shorten compiler diagnostics — pass them through unaltered. Rust diagnostics in particular are best-in-class; Anthropic's RustAssistant numbers depend on them being unaltered.\n70\t\n71\t## 5. Test discipline\n72\t\n73\t- **Failing test first.** Write the failing test, commit it (or stage it visible to the reviewer), then implement.\n74\t- **Test files are read-only during fix-to-spec.** Do not edit a test to make a failing build pass; fix the code.\n75\t- **Property-based tests required** for codec / projection / recovery / round-trip layers. Rust: `proptest` (dev-dep on `fathomdb-schema`, `fathomdb-engine`, `fathomdb-query`). Python: `hypothesis` (in `[dev]` and `[test]` optional deps; install via `pip install -e 'src/python[dev]'`). Scaffolds: `src/rust/crates/<crate>/tests/property_template.rs` and `src/python/tests/test_property_template.py` — replace the trivial property with real round-trip / invariant assertions when domain types land.\n76\t- **No agent-generated oracles.** Tests must encode human intent; do not regenerate snapshot or golden tests autonomously.\n77\t- **Retry budget.** If you hit the same failure mode twice, stop. Re-read the failing test, the relevant ADR, and the relevant `feedback_*.md`. Do not loop a third time without re-thinking; if necessary, `/clear` and reset.\n78\t\n79\t## 6. Comment policy\n80\t\n81\t- **Public-API docstrings:** required for `pub` Rust items, top-level Python functions/classes, exported TS symbols. Document contract: inputs, outputs, errors, panics, invariants.\n82\t- **Internal helpers:** no docstrings unless behavior is non-obvious. Names should carry the meaning.\n83\t- **Inline comments:** why / invariants / hazards only. Never restate what code does. Never reference the current task or PR. (Per CLAUDE-default rules and `feedback_reliability_principles.md`.)\n84\t- **Stale comment > delete.** If a comment no longer matches the code, delete it; do not \"update later.\"\n85\t\n86\t## 7. Subagent rules\n87\t\n88\t- **Main thread orchestrates.** Do not spawn an \"orchestrator\" subagent — the main thread _is_ the orchestrator. (`feedback_orchestrator_thread.md`)\n89\t- **Releases:** main thread plans; delegate coding to `implementer` (in worktree); request diff review from `code-reviewer`. (`feedback_orchestrate_releases.md`)\n90\t- **Subagents win for fan-out.** Parallel research, format-strict review, output isolation. Examples: searching across crates, auditing a diff, generating an ADR draft.\n91\t- **Subagents lose for shared-state edits.** A multi-agent edit pipeline drops tacit context at every handoff. Single-agent for any edit on shared mutable state.\n92\t- **Worktrees** are the unit of isolation. Implementer subagents always operate in a fresh worktree; main thread never edits in a subagent's worktree.\n93\t\n94\t## 8. Iteration discipline\n95\t\n96\t- **Cap retry-budget at ~2 same-issue corrections.** Beyond that, stop, externalize plan to `dev/progress/0.6.0.md`, `/clear`, restart with the plan in front of you.\n97\t- **Compact-aware.** Anything that must survive compaction goes on disk: ADRs, progress logs, plan files, MEMORY entries. Do not rely on chat to remember.\n98\t- **Front-load invariants, end-load tasks.** When prompting yourself or constructing context, put rules near the top, the immediate task near the bottom (lost-in-the-middle).\n99\t\n100\t## 9. Pointers\n101\t\n102\t- **Decisions:** `dev/adr/ADR-0.6.0-decision-index.md`\n103\t- **Interfaces:** `dev/interfaces/{rust,python,typescript,cli,wire}.md`\n104\t- **Progress log:** `dev/progress/0.6.0.md`\n105\t- **Plans:** `dev/plans/`\n106\t- **Research:** `dev/notes/context-research-agentic-best-practices.md` (the best-practices synthesis this file operationalizes)\n107\t- **Memory:** `MEMORY.md` (auto-loaded into Claude Code session start)\n108\t\n109\t## 10. Forbidden patterns\n110\t\n111\tPulled from MEMORY `feedback_*.md`. Violations are correctness bugs, not style preferences.\n112\t\n113\t- **No mocking the database.** Integration tests hit a real database. (`feedback_tdd.md`-adjacent; prior incident.)\n114\t- **No skipping hooks.** Never `--no-verify`, never `--no-gpg-sign` unless explicitly approved.\n115\t- **No backwards-compatibility shims** in pre-1.0 rewrites.\n116\t- **No data migrations** in managed-vec projection releases. (`feedback_no_data_migration.md`)\n117\t- **No `c_char` hardcoded as `i8` or `u8`** at C interop boundaries. (`feedback_cross_platform_rust.md`)\n118\t- **No `pip install` + manual `cargo build` + `cp`** for Python native modules — use `pip install -e python/`. (`feedback_python_native_build.md`)\n119\t- **No `yaml.safe_load` as workflow validator** — use `actionlint`. (`feedback_workflow_validation.md`)\n120\t- **No \"fix in 0.7\"** for reliability bugs. Net-negative LoC on reliability releases. (`feedback_reliability_principles.md`)\n121\t- **No \"green CI = done\"** for releases — install the published wheel and run end-to-end open/close/exit before declaring done. (`feedback_release_verification.md`)\n122\t- **Vector identity belongs to the embedder.** (`project_vector_identity_invariant.md`)\n123\t\n124\t## 11. Permission model (for the Claude Code harness)\n125\t\n126\t`.claude/settings.json` enforces a 3-tier model:\n127\t\n128\t- **read-only** (auto-allowed): `Read`, `Grep`, `Glob`, plus `Bash` for the agent-loop verbs and read-only git/cargo/uv operations.\n129\t- **workspace-write** (auto-allowed): `Edit`, `Write` within the repo; `git add`, `git commit`, `git restore`.\n130\t- **escalated** (denied or asked): destructive ops (`rm`, `mv`, `git reset --hard`, `git clean`); network beyond the package registries (`curl`, `wget`); `git push` requires confirmation.\n131\t\n132\tIf the agent needs an op outside this model, surface it to the user; do not look for workarounds.\n133\t\n134\t## 12. Working with this file\n135\t\n136\t- This file should stay ≤300 lines. If it grows, link out to a scoped doc and reference it.\n137\t- Per-crate `AGENTS.md` files are **not maintained** until each crate has non-scaffold content. Stale > missing.\n138\t- Update this file in the same PR as any change that invalidates one of its rules.\n139\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8996a1e6-f0cf-41f6-bd76-ad56a5a9b42e","uuid":"7059d771-1a4a-4040-ad22-da3cf4c091a0","timestamp":"2026-05-04T02:27:33.528Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-pack5-C1-threadsafe2-rebuild-20260504T022727Z/AGENTS.md","content":"# AGENTS.md — FathomDB\n\nOperating manual for AI coding agents (Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, Aider, Copilot) working in this repo. Cross-vendor convention. This is the canonical agent-instruction file; **no `CLAUDE.md` is maintained** — Claude Code reads `AGENTS.md` natively.\n\nBullet form, prescriptive, ≤300 lines. Link out, do not inline.\n\n## 0. System layers — where each rule fits\n\n- **Invariants layer** — this file (front-loaded, cached, ≤300, bullets).\n- **Index layer** — `dev/adr/ADR-0.6.0-decision-index.md`, `dev/interfaces/*.md`. Linked, never inlined.\n- **Retrieval layer** — grep / glob / read / LSP / tree-sitter map on demand. No local vector index.\n- **Execution layer** — typed dev-loop verbs under `scripts/agent-*.sh` emit structured JSON. Tests are oracle.\n- **Persistence layer** — `dev/progress/<release>.md` + ADR supersession. Compaction-safe.\n- **Permission layer** — three-tier sandbox + worktree-per-task + egress allowlist (`.claude/settings.json`).\n- **Topology layer** — main thread orchestrates; implementer (worktree) + code-reviewer fan out at clean seams; single-agent for shared-state edits.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Invariants — read these first\n\n- **Memory first.** Read `MEMORY.md` and the `feedback_*.md` files it points to before planning any change. They encode prior corrections that override default behavior.\n- **ADRs are authoritative.** Decisions live in `dev/adr/`. Index: `dev/adr/ADR-0.6.0-decision-index.md`. Do not contradict an accepted ADR; propose a successor instead.\n- **TDD is mandatory.** Failing test first; red → green → refactor. Mechanical version bumps and renames are the only exception. (`feedback_tdd.md`)\n- **Stale > missing.** A wrong comment, doc, or ADR is more harmful than its absence. If you cannot maintain something, delete it.\n- **Public surface is contract.** Anything in `dev/interfaces/` or `pub` Rust APIs is a contract; changes need an ADR or interface-doc update in the same PR.\n\n## 2. Repo shape\n\n- **Rust workspace** under `src/rust/crates/` — 7 crates: `fathomdb`, `fathomdb-cli`, `fathomdb-engine`, `fathomdb-query`, `fathomdb-schema`, `fathomdb-embedder`, `fathomdb-embedder-api`.\n- **Python bindings** under `src/python/` (package: `fathomdb`).\n- **TypeScript bindings** under `src/ts/`.\n- **Public docs** under `docs/` (MkDocs-built).\n- **Internal engineering docs** under `dev/`: `adr/`, `interfaces/`, `progress/`, `plans/`, `tmp/`.\n\n## 3. Build / test / lint commands\n\nUse the typed dev-loop verbs (Phase 2). Each emits **concise output on pass, structured diagnostic on fail**, with full output spilled to `/tmp/fathomdb-agent-<verb>-<pid>.log` when capped.\n\n| Verb      | Script                         | Purpose                                                           |\n| --------- | ------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| build     | `./scripts/agent-build.sh`     | Compile workspace (Rust + Python install + TS build if installed) |\n| lint      | `./scripts/agent-lint.sh`      | clippy + ruff + markdownlint + prettier --check + lychee          |\n| typecheck | `./scripts/agent-typecheck.sh` | cargo check + pyright + tsc --noEmit                              |\n| test      | `./scripts/agent-test.sh`      | cargo test + pytest                                               |\n| verify    | `./scripts/agent-verify.sh`    | lint → typecheck → test (short-circuits on first fail)            |\n\nMarkdown lint covers `AGENTS.md`, `dev/plans/`, `dev/progress/`, README files, and root metadata. Pre-existing legacy under `dev/adr/`, `dev/design/`, `dev/agents/`, `dev/deps/`, etc. is excluded — clean up incrementally when touching those files. Auto-fix: `npm run format:md` (prettier --write) + `./node_modules/.bin/markdownlint-cli2 --fix`.\n\nRun `./scripts/agent-verify.sh` after every meaningful edit. Do not ship a PR with verify failing.\n\nThe broader CI gate is `./scripts/check.sh` (adds mkdocs build); the agent-loop gate is `agent-verify.sh`. Long-run test variants (e.g. AC-021 60 s window, AC-059b ~1000-iteration cursor-race fixture) are exercised only via `scripts/check.sh` with `AGENT_LONG=1`; `agent-verify.sh` skips them for runtime budget.\n\n### One-time setup\n\n- Rust toolchain: stable per `rust-version` in `Cargo.toml`. clippy + rustfmt come with rustup defaults.\n- Python dev tooling: `pip install -e 'src/python[dev]'` — installs `pytest`, `hypothesis`, `ruff`, `pyright`. Without this, the Python lint/typecheck/test steps emit a skip notice and pass without exercising.\n- TypeScript: `cd src/ts && npm install` if you intend to touch TS. Without this, TS verbs skip.\n- Markdown tooling: `npm install` at repo root — installs `markdownlint-cli2` + `prettier`. `cargo install --locked lychee` for link checking (one-time). All wired up by `./scripts/bootstrap.sh`.\n\n## 4. Verification ordering\n\nRun in latency order; short-circuit on first failure:\n\n1. **lint** (clippy / ruff) — fastest signal, catches most style + correctness issues\n2. **typecheck** (cargo check / pyright / tsc) — catches type errors before tests run them\n3. **unit tests** (`agent-test.sh`)\n4. **integration tests** — opt-in, gated by feature/env flag; not part of `agent-verify`\n\nDo not paraphrase, summarize, or shorten compiler diagnostics — pass them through unaltered. Rust diagnostics in particular are best-in-class; Anthropic's RustAssistant numbers depend on them being unaltered.\n\n## 5. Test discipline\n\n- **Failing test first.** Write the failing test, commit it (or stage it visible to the reviewer), then implement.\n- **Test files are read-only during fix-to-spec.** Do not edit a test to make a failing build pass; fix the code.\n- **Property-based tests required** for codec / projection / recovery / round-trip layers. Rust: `proptest` (dev-dep on `fathomdb-schema`, `fathomdb-engine`, `fathomdb-query`). Python: `hypothesis` (in `[dev]` and `[test]` optional deps; install via `pip install -e 'src/python[dev]'`). Scaffolds: `src/rust/crates/<crate>/tests/property_template.rs` and `src/python/tests/test_property_template.py` — replace the trivial property with real round-trip / invariant assertions when domain types land.\n- **No agent-generated oracles.** Tests must encode human intent; do not regenerate snapshot or golden tests autonomously.\n- **Retry budget.** If you hit the same failure mode twice, stop. Re-read the failing test, the relevant ADR, and the relevant `feedback_*.md`. Do not loop a third time without re-thinking; if necessary, `/clear` and reset.\n\n## 6. Comment policy\n\n- **Public-API docstrings:** required for `pub` Rust items, top-level Python functions/classes, exported TS symbols. Document contract: inputs, outputs, errors, panics, invariants.\n- **Internal helpers:** no docstrings unless behavior is non-obvious. Names should carry the meaning.\n- **Inline comments:** why / invariants / hazards only. Never restate what code does. Never reference the current task or PR. (Per CLAUDE-default rules and `feedback_reliability_principles.md`.)\n- **Stale comment > delete.** If a comment no longer matches the code, delete it; do not \"update later.\"\n\n## 7. Subagent rules\n\n- **Main thread orchestrates.** Do not spawn an \"orchestrator\" subagent — the main thread _is_ the orchestrator. (`feedback_orchestrator_thread.md`)\n- **Releases:** main thread plans; delegate coding to `implementer` (in worktree); request diff review from `code-reviewer`. (`feedback_orchestrate_releases.md`)\n- **Subagents win for fan-out.** Parallel research, format-strict review, output isolation. Examples: searching across crates, auditing a diff, generating an ADR draft.\n- **Subagents lose for shared-state edits.** A multi-agent edit pipeline drops tacit context at every handoff. Single-agent for any edit on shared mutable state.\n- **Worktrees** are the unit of isolation. Implementer subagents always operate in a fresh worktree; main thread never edits in a subagent's worktree.\n\n## 8. Iteration discipline\n\n- **Cap retry-budget at ~2 same-issue corrections.** Beyond that, stop, externalize plan to `dev/progress/0.6.0.md`, `/clear`, restart with the plan in front of you.\n- **Compact-aware.** Anything that must survive compaction goes on disk: ADRs, progress logs, plan files, MEMORY entries. Do not rely on chat to remember.\n- **Front-load invariants, end-load tasks.** When prompting yourself or constructing context, put rules near the top, the immediate task near the bottom (lost-in-the-middle).\n\n## 9. Pointers\n\n- **Decisions:** `dev/adr/ADR-0.6.0-decision-index.md`\n- **Interfaces:** `dev/interfaces/{rust,python,typescript,cli,wire}.md`\n- **Progress log:** `dev/progress/0.6.0.md`\n- **Plans:** `dev/plans/`\n- **Research:** `dev/notes/context-research-agentic-best-practices.md` (the best-practices synthesis this file operationalizes)\n- **Memory:** `MEMORY.md` (auto-loaded into Claude Code session start)\n\n## 10. Forbidden patterns\n\nPulled from MEMORY `feedback_*.md`. Violations are correctness bugs, not style preferences.\n\n- **No mocking the database.** Integration tests hit a real database. (`feedback_tdd.md`-adjacent; prior incident.)\n- **No skipping hooks.** Never `--no-verify`, never `--no-gpg-sign` unless explicitly approved.\n- **No backwards-compatibility shims** in pre-1.0 rewrites.\n- **No data migrations** in managed-vec projection releases. (`feedback_no_data_migration.md`)\n- **No `c_char` hardcoded as `i8` or `u8`** at C interop boundaries. (`feedback_cross_platform_rust.md`)\n- **No `pip install` + manual `cargo build` + `cp`** for Python native modules — use `pip install -e python/`. (`feedback_python_native_build.md`)\n- **No `yaml.safe_load` as workflow validator** — use `actionlint`. (`feedback_workflow_validation.md`)\n- **No \"fix in 0.7\"** for reliability bugs. Net-negative LoC on reliability releases. (`feedback_reliability_principles.md`)\n- **No \"green CI = done\"** for releases — install the published wheel and run end-to-end open/close/exit before declaring done. (`feedback_release_verification.md`)\n- **Vector identity belongs to the embedder.** (`project_vector_identity_invariant.md`)\n\n## 11. Permission model (for the Claude Code harness)\n\n`.claude/settings.json` enforces a 3-tier model:\n\n- **read-only** (auto-allowed): `Read`, `Grep`, `Glob`, plus `Bash` for the agent-loop verbs and read-only git/cargo/uv operations.\n- **workspace-write** (auto-allowed): `Edit`, `Write` within the repo; `git add`, `git commit`, `git restore`.\n- **escalated** (denied or asked): destructive ops (`rm`, `mv`, `git reset --hard`, `git clean`); network beyond the package registries (`curl`, `wget`); `git push` requires confirmation.\n\nIf the agent needs an op outside this model, surface it to the user; do not look for workarounds.\n\n## 12. Working with this file\n\n- This file should stay ≤300 lines. If it grows, link out to a scoped doc and reference it.\n- Per-crate `AGENTS.md` files are **not maintained** until each crate has non-scaffold content. Stale > missing.\n- Update this file in the same PR as any change that invalidates one of its rules.\n","numLines":139,"startLine":1,"totalLines":139}}}
