n time is SQLITE_OK (0) for every reader worker.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"reader_workers_consume_lookaside_slots_after_warmup_read\",\n      \"file\": \"src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/reader_pool.rs\",\n      \"red_failure_mode\": \"Compile-time: method `reader_lookaside_used_per_worker_for_test` does not exist on `fathomdb_engine::Engine` (E0599). Pre-implementation. Once compiling, this test would also fail at runtime if lookaside were misconfigured (e.g. ordered after a PRAGMA so SQLite silently ignored it) because `SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr would remain 0 after warmup. Initially also failed at runtime when the test read `current` instead of `hiwtr` (slots returned to the pool when the search transaction closed) — fixed by asserting on hiwtr, which is the right semantic for 'at least one slot was honored at any point'.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"lookaside_config\": {\n    \"slot_size_bytes\": 1200,\n    \"slot_count\": 500,\n    \"applied_via\": \"raw FFI: rusqlite::ffi::sqlite3_db_config(handle, ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, NULL, 1200, 500). rusqlite 0.31's safe `set_db_config` wrapper only supports the boolean DbConfig::* variants; `SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` is explicitly commented out in `rusqlite-0.31.0/src/config.rs`. Used the named symbol `ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` (= 1001) rather than a magic number per cross-platform Rust convention.\",\n    \"ordering_assertion_rc\": \"0 (SQLITE_OK) for every reader worker, captured at open time before any PRAGMA / prepare ran on the connection. Captured per-worker into `Engine::reader_lookaside_rcs: Vec<i32>` (allow(dead_code) in release; read by `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` in debug).\"\n  },\n  \"lookaside_used_evidence\": {\n    \"method\": \"Debug-only `ReaderRequest::LookasideStatus` request broadcast to every worker (not round-robin); each worker calls `sqlite3_db_status(SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED)` and returns the high-water-mark out-param. `current` was tried first but decays as transactions finalize so it is unreliable for post-warmup evidence; `hiwtr` is the correct latched signal that lookaside was honored at any point.\",\n    \"after_warmup_test_workload\": \"READER_POOL_SIZE * 8 = 64 dispatched `engine.search('warmup')` calls (each routed round-robin to one of the 8 workers) on a fresh empty engine, search() returns Err but still parses + prepares + steps which exercises the lookaside arena.\",\n    \"hiwtr_per_worker\": [57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57],\n    \"interpretation\": \"Every worker has hiwtr=57 slots used (well below the configured 500-slot capacity, ~11%). Uniformity across workers reflects the round-robin dispatch + the fact that `engine.search('warmup')` exercises the same transaction shape on each. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload is more allocation-heavy and would push hiwtr higher; the test gate is 'consumed > 0', not 'saturated'.\"\n  },\n  \"ac017_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"profile\": \"release\",\n      \"notes\": \"Run via `cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture`; `test ac_017_vector_projection_freshness_p99_le_five_seconds ... ok` in 14.64 s wall.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ac018_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"drain_ms\": 95,\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"notes\": \"release; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95; well under the 2 s gate. Slightly higher than G.0's 51 ms (run-to-run; G.0 itself reported 56 ms in F.0 baseline).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ac020_runs\": [\n    {\"run\": 1, \"sequential_ms\": 582, \"concurrent_ms\": 153, \"bound_ms\": 109, \"speedup\": 3.804, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 2, \"sequential_ms\": 547, \"concurrent_ms\": 161, \"bound_ms\": 102, \"speedup\": 3.398, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 3, \"sequential_ms\": 593, \"concurrent_ms\": 168, \"bound_ms\": 111, \"speedup\": 3.530, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 4, \"sequential_ms\": 563, \"concurrent_ms\": 181, \"bound_ms\": 105, \"speedup\": 3.110, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 5, \"sequential_ms\": 503, \"concurrent_ms\": 118, \"bound_ms\": 94,  \"speedup\": 4.263, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false}\n  ],\n  \"ac020_summary\": {\n    \"sequential_ms\": {\"min\": 503, \"median\": 563, \"max\": 593, \"stddev\": 33.40},\n    \"concurrent_ms\": {\"min\": 118, \"median\": 161, \"max\": 181, \"stddev\": 22.83},\n    \"speedup\":      {\"min\": 3.110, \"median\": 3.530, \"max\": 4.263, \"stddev\": 0.428}\n  },\n  \"comparison_to_g0_baseline\": {\n    \"g0_baseline_of_record\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median\": 552,\n      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 168,\n      \"speedup_median\": 3.339,\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 11.89,\n      \"n\": 5\n    },\n    \"g1_observed\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median\": 563,\n      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 161,\n      \"speedup_median\": 3.530,\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 22.83,\n      \"n\": 5\n    },\n    \"deltas\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median_delta\": \"+11 ms (+2.0%) — within run-to-run noise\",\n      \"concurrent_ms_median_delta\": \"-7 ms (-4.2%) — improvement, but inside G.0's 1*stddev band (11.89 ms)\",\n      \"speedup_median_delta\": \"+0.191x (+5.7%) — no ratio worsening\",\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev_delta\": \"+10.94 ms — G.1 run shows higher variance, partly driven by run 5 (118 ms) and run 4 (181 ms); not a regression but a wider band that loosens the KEEP threshold further on this sample\"\n    },\n    \"keep_threshold_evaluation\": {\n      \"rule\": \"concurrent_median < g0_baseline.concurrent_median - 1 * g0_baseline.stddev\",\n      \"threshold_ms\": 156.11,\n      \"observed_ms\": 161,\n      \"verdict\": \"miss by 4.89 ms (~0.41 * stddev); does NOT meet KEEP threshold\",\n      \"ratio_floor_evaluation\": {\n        \"rule\": \"speedup_median >= g0_baseline.speedup_median\",\n        \"threshold\": 3.339,\n        \"observed\": 3.530,\n        \"verdict\": \"pass; no ratio worsening\"\n      }\n    }\n  },\n  \"optional_sweep_results\": null,\n  \"optional_sweep_notes\": \"Did not run the [128, 250, 500, 1000] x {512, 1200} sweep grid. Spec §2 makes it optional ('do NOT bake the sweep into the production code path'); G.0 telemetry already pointed at 1200 x 500 as the right canonical sizing for the sticky reader topology and the small-allocation footprint of the FTS5 / vec0 hot stacks. If the orchestrator + reviewer want the sweep before deciding KEEP vs INCONCLUSIVE, it can be done as a follow-up under a debug-gated env knob without re-opening the public surface; the lookaside-call helper is already isolated in `configure_reader_lookaside`.\",\n  \"unexpected_observations\": [\n    \"AC-020 run-to-run variance widened on this G.1 sample (concurrent stddev 22.83 ms vs G.0's 11.89 ms). Run 5 in particular hit 118 ms / 4.263x — the best concurrent number observed in any G-phase run on this host so far — while run 4 hit 181 ms / 3.110x. The wider band loosens the formal KEEP threshold but suggests lookaside is doing real work when contention is the bottleneck (run 5 is plausibly an arena-pressure best-case). A larger N (e.g. N=10) would tighten the verdict; the spec calls for N=5 so I did not run more.\",\n    \"Sequential_median moved +11 ms (552 -> 563). Within noise, but consistent with the documented 'lookaside has a small overhead per allocation when the slot pool is healthy' note in the SQLite docs; sequential perf shouldn't IMPROVE from lookaside on a single-threaded fixture (no malloc-arena contention to remove), and a small regression in the 1-2% band is expected and tolerable.\",\n    \"Per-worker `LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr after warmup is uniform at 57 slots/worker, which is ~11% of the 500-slot capacity. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload would push that higher (the warmup test does only a 64-call light-search